## Context Manifest

_Generated by context-gathering agent on 2026-03-02_

### How This Feature Fits Into the SAM Workflow

The SAM (Stateless Agent Methodology) workflow produces plan artifacts during `/add-new-feature` and then implements them in `/implement-feature`. The six tasks in this plan introduce a lifecycle policy that addresses a structural gap: once created, plan artifacts were never updated, leaving them as write-once snapshots that diverge silently from what was actually built.

The workflow that this feature policy governs flows in three phases. During Phase 1 (`/add-new-feature`), the `feature-researcher` agent produces `plan/feature-context-{slug}.md`, the `codebase-analyzer` agent produces `plan/codebase/{FOCUS}.md` (optional), the `python-cli-design-spec` agent produces `plan/architect-{slug}.md`, and the `swarm-task-planner` agent produces the task file `plan/tasks-{N}-{slug}.md`. The `context-gathering` agent then populates the `## Context Manifest` section inside the task file. All of these artifacts are written once and never revisited.

During Phase 2 (`/implement-feature`), the orchestrator queries `implementation_manager.py` for ready tasks, then delegates each to its assigned agent via the `/start-task` skill. The `/start-task` skill marks the task `in-progress`, writes `.claude/context/active-task-{session_id}.json` for hook consumption, and instructs the agent to implement against the task's acceptance criteria. A `PostToolUse` hook fires on every Write/Edit/Bash call and updates `LastActivity` in the task file. When the sub-agent finishes, a `SubagentStop` hook sets the task to `complete` and writes the `completed` timestamp.

During Phase 3 (`/complete-implementation`), six quality gate phases run sequentially. Phase 6 launches the `context-refinement` agent, which currently updates only the task file's `## Context Manifest` section with a `### Discovered During Implementation` subsection. This is the only point in the workflow where any plan artifact receives any update. The feature-context and architect spec files receive no updates whatsoever — they remain as they were created.

This feature adds divergence recording at the `/start-task` level (Step 5a) and expands the `context-refinement` agent's scope at `/complete-implementation` Phase 6 (new Steps 5-8) so that plan artifacts receive annotations describing what actually changed during implementation. A canonical policy document (`.claude/docs/plan-artifact-lifecycle.md`) is created to hold the taxonomy and rules, and `TASK_FILE_FORMAT.md` is extended with a `divergence-notes` counter field.

### What Each Task Produces and Why the Order Matters

T1 creates `.claude/docs/plan-artifact-lifecycle.md` — the canonical policy document that T2, T3, T4, and T5 all reference via relative links. T1 must complete before T2, T3, or T5 can write their references, because those tasks verify that the link target exists before writing. T6 runs in parallel with T1 because it writes to `TASK_FILE_FORMAT.md` only, with no dependency on the policy document.

T2, T3, and T5 run in parallel after T1 completes. They write to three distinct files with no overlap: T2 writes to `.claude/rules/local-workflow.md`, T3 writes to `.claude/skills/start-task/SKILL.md`, and T5 writes to `plugins/python3-development/agents/context-refinement.md`.

T4 runs last because it updates `.claude/skills/complete-implementation/SKILL.md` to describe the expanded Phase 6 behavior, and that description must accurately reference what T5 added to the `context-refinement` agent. T4 reads `context-refinement.md` to confirm the `DIVERGENCE_REQUIRING_REVIEW` block name before writing its reference.

### Critical File: `.claude/docs/plan-artifact-lifecycle.md` (T1)

This file does not yet exist. The implementer creates it. Its full required content is specified in `plan/architect-plan-artifact-lifecycle.md`, sections "Policy Document: `.claude/docs/plan-artifact-lifecycle.md`", "Artifact Classification Taxonomy", "Resolved Design Questions Q1-Q5", "Divergence Recording During Task Execution", "Extended Context-Refinement Agent", and "Backward Compatibility".

The file must contain exactly nine sections in this order: Purpose and Scope, Artifact Classification, Rules for Human-Decision Artifacts, Rules for Generated Artifacts, Divergence Detection, Divergence Classification, Divergence Recording, Divergence Reporting, Backward Compatibility.

Cross-references in this file point to: `.claude/rules/local-workflow.md`, `.claude/docs/TASK_FILE_FORMAT.md`, `.claude/skills/start-task/SKILL.md`, and `plugins/python3-development/agents/context-refinement.md`. All four paths must be verified with the `Read` tool before use. The relative paths from `.claude/docs/plan-artifact-lifecycle.md` to these files are `./rules/local-workflow.md`, `./TASK_FILE_FORMAT.md`, `./skills/start-task/SKILL.md`, and `./../plugins/python3-development/agents/context-refinement.md`. Verify existence before writing.

The divergence note format block in this document defines the format agents use in task files:

```text
## Divergence Notes

### DN-1: {Brief title}

- **Plan artifact**: plan/architect-{slug}.md, section "{section name}"
- **Plan claim**: "{quoted text from plan artifact}"
- **Actual implementation**: "{what was actually done and why}"
- **Classification**: design-refinement | intent-divergence
- **Recorded**: {ISO timestamp}
```

The divergence threshold table (from the Q1 resolution in the architecture spec) classifies five change types: implementation detail differs from architect spec (design-refinement, auto-record), approach differs but achieves same goal from backlog item (design-refinement, auto-record and annotate), scope expanded or reduced beyond backlog item (intent-divergence, flag for review), goal redefined or abandoned (intent-divergence), constraint from grooming output violated (intent-divergence).

